In article &lt;747@cunixc.columbia.edu&gt; alan@cunixc.columbia.edu (Alan Crosswell) writes:
&gt;Newsgroups: comp.protocols.tcp-ip
&gt;Re: Domain name/subnet relationship.
&gt;...There are now many "MX" servers on the Internet that respond to
&gt;domain lookups for BITNET and UUCP hosts.

Hmmm, why not have the official inter-network gateways (like
cunyvm.cuny.edu) claim MX for all of "bitnet."?  Three benefits:
	(1) Our sendmail.cf wouldn't have to special-case the .bitnet
	    (or .csnet or .dec or .xerox or ...) pseudo-domain and
	    know to send it off to the appropriate gateway.  Whoever
	    wants it can claim it themselves.
	(2) It would make it easier to move the gateway the next time
	    - just shuffle a few MX records.
	(3) There could be several gateways with (possibly) varying
	    levels of MX "costs" advertised, all active at once to
	    share the load, so (2) won't happen so soon.
Similar tricks could be played with other top level pseudo-domains.

Problems?  Holes?  Fallacies?
-=-
